# ### Winding Number as an Integral
# 
# The winding number can also be written as a compact formula using the unit vector $\mathbf{d}_d$, defined as
# 
# $$
# \mathbf{d}_d = \frac{\mathbf{d}}{|\mathbf{d}|}
# $$
# 
# The vector $\mathbf{d}_d(k)$ is well defined for all $k$ because $\mathbf{d}(k) \ne 0$.
# 
# You can check easily that the winding number $\nu$ is given by
# 
# $$
# \nu = \frac{1}{2\pi} \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} \left( \mathbf{d}_d(k) \times \frac{d}{dk} \mathbf{d}_d(k) \right)_z \, dk 
# $$
# 
# To calculate $\nu$ directly from the bulk momentum-space Hamiltonian, note that it is off-diagonal (in the basis of eigenstates of the chiral symmetry operator $\sigma_z$),
# 
# $$
# H(k) = \begin{pmatrix}
# 0 & h(k) \\
# h^*(k) & 0
# \end{pmatrix}, \quad \text{where } h(k) = d_x(k) - i d_y(k) 
# $$
# 
# The winding number of $\mathbf{d}(k)$ can be written as an integral using the complex logarithm function, $\log(|h| e^{i \arg h}) = \log |h| + i \arg h$. It is easy to check that
# 
# $$
# \nu = \frac{1}{2\pi i} \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} dk \, \frac{d}{dk} \log h(k)
# $$
# 
# Here, during the calculation of the integral, the branch cut for the logarithm is always shifted so that the derivative is well defined. The above integral is always real, since $|h(k = -\pi)| = |h(k = \pi)|$.
# 

# In[5]:


# Parameters
N = 20              # Number of unit cells
M = 2 * N           # Total number of sites
t1 = 0.5            # Intracell hopping (topological case: t1 < t2)
t2 = 1.0            # Intercell hopping
k_vals = np.linspace(-np.pi, np.pi, N)


# In[6]:


# bulk momentum-space Hamiltonian
def h(k, t1=1.0, t2=0.5):
    return t1 + t2 * np.exp(-1j * k)

# Winding number calc.
def compute_winding_number(t1=1.0, t2=0.5, N=1000):
    k_vals = np.linspace(-np.pi, np.pi, N, endpoint=False)
    hk = h(k_vals, t1, t2)

    # Compute log(h(k)) and its derivative
    log_hk = np.log(hk)
    dlog_dk = np.gradient(log_hk, k_vals)

    # Integrate
    winding_integral = np.trapz(dlog_dk, k_vals)
    winding_number = winding_integral / (2j * np.pi)

    return np.round(winding_number.real)


# In[7]:


# h(k) function
hk_vals = h(k_vals, t1, t2)

# winding number
winding = compute_winding_number(t1, t2)
print(f"winding number = {winding}")


# In[8]:


plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
plt.plot(hk_vals.real, hk_vals.imag)
plt.plot(0, 0, 'ro', label='Origin')
plt.xlabel('Re[h(k)]')
plt.ylabel('Im[h(k)]')
plt.title('Trajectory of $h(k)$ in Complex Plane')
plt.grid(True)
plt.axis('equal')
plt.legend()
plt.show()


