# ## Bound States at Domain Walls
# 
# Edge states in the SSH model are not limited to the physical ends of an open chain; they can also appear at **domain walls** between topologically distinct insulating regions within the same chain.
# 
# This can be intuitively understood in the **fully dimerized limit**. Consider a system with alternating domains of different dimerization patterns. At the boundaries between these domains—called **domain walls**—new localized states can emerge.
# 
# There are two types of domain walls:
# 
# * A **single isolated site**, which hosts a **zero-energy state**:
# 
#   $$
#   \hat{H} \left( |6_B\rangle - |7_B\rangle \right) = 0
#   $$
# 
# * A **trimer**, where a zero-energy eigenstate is formed by an **odd superposition** of the two end sites.
# 
# Just like the edge states at the ends of the chain, these **domain-wall states** are **sublattice-polarized**—the wavefunction has support only on one sublattice.
# ![5](5.png) 
# 
# From a perfect dimerized configuration, **only an even number of domain walls can be introduced**. This means that if a domain wall localizes a state on one sublattice, there must be another domain wall somewhere else (possibly at the system edge) localizing a state on the opposite sublattice.
# 
# Now, consider a domain wall configuration **away from the fully dimerized limit**. The domain wall modes remain **exponentially localized**, but their wavefunctions now **penetrate slightly into the bulk**, forming **evanescent tails**. If two domain walls are separated by $M$ unit cells, their corresponding localized edge states **hybridize**, forming bonding and anti-bonding combinations. At **half-filling**, only the **lower-energy (bonding) state** is occupied.
# 
# This bonding state:
# 
# * Contains **one electron**,
# * Has a wavefunction **symmetrically localized** on both domain walls,
# * And therefore, **each domain wall carries half an electronic charge**.
# 
# This effect is a hallmark of **charge fractionalization**, and provides a striking consequence of the topological nature of the SSH model.
# 

# In[15]:


# Define two regions (topological and trivial)
t1_left = 0.5
t2_left = 1.0
t1_right = 1.0
t2_right = 0.5

# Initialize Hamiltonian
H = np.zeros((M, M))

# Fill Hamiltonian with left region (topological)
for i in range(0, M//2 - 1, 2):
    H[i, i+1] = t1_left
    H[i+1, i] = t1_left

for i in range(1, M//2 - 1, 2):
    H[i, i+1] = t2_left
    H[i+1, i] = t2_left

# Fill Hamiltonian with right region (trivial)
for i in range(M//2, M - 1, 2):
    H[i, i+1] = t1_right
    H[i+1, i] = t1_right

for i in range(M//2 + 1, M - 1, 2):
    H[i, i+1] = t2_right
    H[i+1, i] = t2_right

# Diagonalize
eigenvalues, eigenvectors = np.linalg.eigh(H)

# Sort eigenvalues and reorder eigenvectors accordingly
sorted_indices = np.argsort(eigenvalues)
eigenvalues = eigenvalues[sorted_indices]
eigenvectors = eigenvectors[:, sorted_indices]


# In[16]:


# Plot eigenvalues
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.scatter(range(M), eigenvalues, color='darkblue', s=30)
plt.axhline(0, color='gray', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.8)
plt.xlabel('Eigenvalue Index')
plt.ylabel('Energy')
plt.title('SSH Model with Domain Wall')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()


# In[17]:


# Find index of eigenvalue closest to 0
idx_zero = np.argmin(np.abs(eigenvalues))
bound_state = eigenvectors[:, idx_zero]

# Plot amplitude
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.plot(np.abs(bound_state)**2, 'o-', color='darkblue')
plt.xlabel('Site')
plt.ylabel(r'$|\psi|^2$')
plt.title('Domain Wall State Localization')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()


# In[18]:


# Set up the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 4))
line, = ax.plot([], [], 'o-', color='darkblue')
title = ax.set_title("")
ax.set_xlim(0, M)
ax.set_ylim(-0.01, 0.4)
ax.set_xlabel("Site index")
ax.set_ylabel(r'$|\psi|^2$')


# In[19]:


# Initialization function
def init():
    line.set_data([], [])
    title.set_text("")
    return line, title

# Animation function
def animate(i):
    psi = eigenvectors[:, i]
    # Compute probability density |ψ_n(i)|^2 for each site i
    prob_density = np.abs(psi)**2
    line.set_data(np.arange(M), prob_density)
    title.set_text(f"Eigenstate {i+1}, Energy = {eigenvalues[i]:.3f}")
    return line, title


